category=Getting Started
description=<p>This examples shows you how to list all the words that are found in a piece of text--perhaps to create a dictionary or concordance for a text file, or to compare two or more texts statistically.</p>
discussion=<p>This custom function is called with a statement such as one of the following:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">put</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> uniqueWordsOf(field &quot;Text&quot;) into myWordsList</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">put</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> uniqueWordsOf(myVariable) into field &quot;Words&quot;</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">put</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> uniqueWordsOf(URL &quot;file:List.txt&quot;) into theWords</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat</font> control structure checks each word in turn, creating an <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>array</i></font> variable named &quot;wordsList&quot;. Each element of &quot;wordsList&quot; is associated with a different word; the element's key is the word, and the element's contents is a number. For example, if the first word of the string is &quot;Cans&quot;, then after the first word is processed, the array &quot;wordsList&quot; contains one element, named &quot;Cans&quot;, which contains the number 1.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>When a word is processed, the handler adds 1 to the element corresponding to that word. If there is no array element with that name already, one is created automatically by the <font face="Courier" size="11">add</font> command. In general, changing a variable, a chunk in a variable, or an element in an array variable creates the variable, chunk, or element automatically, if it doesn't already exist. If there is already an element with that name--that is, if the word already exists in the array--1 is added to that existing element.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>After all the words have been processed, the function exits the <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat</font> loop. At this point, the array variable &quot;wordsList&quot; contains an element for each unique word, whose name is the word itself. The keys of &quot;wordsList&quot;, therefore, is a list of all the unique words in the string.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>This form of word-by-word processing is possible because Transcript uses chunk expressions to manage text. A chunk expression is a way of describing a specific portion of a container. Transcript can directly address individual words, characters, lines, and items (delimited by any character). For more details on chunk expressions, see the section on <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>Using Chunk Expressions</i></font> in the <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>User's Guide</i></font>. In this example, we use the <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat for each</font> chunk form of the <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat</font> control structure:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">repeat</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">for</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> each word thisWord in theString</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>This <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat</font> structure loops through each word in the parameter &quot;theString&quot;, putting the current word into a variable called &quot;thisWord&quot;. You can also loop through other chunk types in a <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat</font> structure, processing each <font face="Courier" size="11">character</font>, <font face="Courier" size="11">line</font>, or <font face="Courier" size="11">item</font>.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>You may have noticed that there's potential additional functionality in this function. The &quot;wordsList&quot; array contains all the information needed to create a frequency list of words, since each element's content is equal to the number of times that word occurs in the string. You can use the <font face="Courier" size="11">combine</font> command to turn the array into a text list:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">combine</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> wordsList using </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">return</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> and tab</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">sort</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> the lines of wordsList</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">return</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> wordsList</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>With the addition of the above three statements, the function returns a frequency count, rather than just the list of words. Each line of the returned value starts with a word, followed by a tab character and the number of times that word occurs. The <font face="Courier" size="11">sort</font> command is not strictly necessary here--we didn't sort the list returned from the original version of this function--but it puts the list in neat alphabetical order.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>We can also return the list in frequency order instead of word order, simply by changing the <font face="Courier" size="11">sort</font> command above to the following:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">sort</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> the lines of wordsList numeric by last word of each</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><b>A note on efficiency:</b></font></p>\n<p>This example uses the <font face="Courier" size="11">repeat for each</font> word form of the repeat control structure. When looping over chunk types in a string, this form is the fastest. The following repeat structure is functionally equivalent to the one in this example, but is much slower:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">repeat</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">with</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> x = 1 to the </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#FF0000">number</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> of words in theString</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">    </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">add</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> 1 to wordsList[word x of theString]</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">end</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">repeat</font></p>
level=2
licensed=false
name=Listing all the unique words in a piece of text
solution=<p><font color="#0000FF">function</font> uniqueWordsOf theString</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">repeat</font> <font color="#980517">for</font> each word thisWord in theString</p>\n<p>    <font color="#0000FF">add</font> 1 to wordsList[thisWord] <font color="#68228B">-- array variable</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">end</font> <font color="#980517">repeat</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">return</font> the <font color="#F88017">keys</font> of wordsList <font color="#68228B">-- the list of words</font></p>\n<p><font color="#980517">end</font> uniqueWordsOf</p>
title=Listing all the unique words in a piece of text